{"id":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.022101","title":{"value":"Thermophoresis of confined colloids in the near-contact limit","format":"html+mathml"},"publisher":{"name":"APS"},"journal":{"id":"PRFLUIDS","abbreviatedName":"Phys. Rev. Fluids","name":"Physical Review Fluids"},"issue":{"number":"2"},"volume":{"number":"1"},"pageStart":"022101","hasArticleId":true,"date":"2016-06-15","numPages":6,"articleType":"rapid","identifiers":{"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.022101"},"rights":{"rightsStatement":"©2016 American Physical Society","copyrightYear":2016,"copyrightHolders":[{"name":"American Physical Society"}]},"authors":[{"type":"Person","name":"Ehud Yariv","firstname":"Ehud","surname":"Yariv","affiliationIds":["a1"]}],"affiliations":[{"id":"a1","name":"Department of Mathematics, Technion–Israel Institute of Technology, Haifa 32000, Israel"}],"abstract":{"value":"<p>In a recent Letter [<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.138302\"><span>Phys. Rev. Lett.</span> <b>116</b>, 138302 (2016)</a>] Würger calculated the thermophoretic velocity of a colloidal sphere towards a solid boundary due to an imposed temperature gradient perpendicular to that wall in the limit where the particle-wall separation distance <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math></span> is small compared to the particle radius <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math></span>. Würger obtained the approximation <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo><mo form=\"prefix\">ln</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2.25</mn><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> for the particle velocity <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi></math></span> towards the wall, <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span> being the corresponding velocity in the bulk. In deriving that approximation an <i>ad hoc</i> procedure was employed to circumvent the calculation of a diverging integral that emerges in the course of a lubrication analysis. We show here how to systematically address this problem, obtaining the approximation <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>[</mo><mo form=\"prefix\">ln</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>0.1087</mn><mo>]</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span>.</p>","format":"html+mathml"},"classificationSchemes":{"physh":{"disciplines":[{"id":"2bd35371-7fda-477a-8e1a-c346c797a232","label":"Polymers & Soft Matter"}],"concepts":[{"id":"f7f8d0e5-5d79-44a2-998b-6ed48fe0d6a4","label":"Thermophoresis","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"},"primary":true},{"id":"2cea1c8c-c8ee-4576-a697-73e0371d9428","label":"Lubrication","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"fa2c0c80-ce03-4933-9dcf-0269b613e73f","label":"Osmotic interactions","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"f033dcc0-0f19-42c3-b48f-bfe11a85a24b","label":"Confinement","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"d1dc41a8-e63f-419e-88a5-8e7aeb3cd01d","label":"Fluid-particle interactions","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"17d6ffbe-b5db-4c92-b602-93b78f871d79","label":"Electrokinetic flows","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","la